\description{
Builds, for each group (typically a species), a rarefaction/accumulation
curve of an intraspecific variability metric as a function of the number
of individuals sampled, and estimates the sample size \verb{n*} at which that
variability \emph{stabilises} -- the trait-based analogue of a species
accumulation (rarefaction) curve. For each sub-sample size
\code{n} = 2, 3, ..., N_g, \code{n_perm} sub-samples of \code{n} individuals are
drawn at random \strong{without replacement} from the group's N_g
individuals, the metric is computed on each, and the draws are summarised
by their mean and a resampling quantile band.
}
\details{
The behaviour of the curve, and therefore the meaning of "stabilises",
depends fundamentally on the \emph{kind} of metric (see also Violle et al.,
2012; Gotelli & Colwell, 2001):

\describe{
\item{\strong{Dispersion metrics} (\code{"variance"}, \code{"sd"}, \code{"cv"})}{The sample
variance is an \emph{unbiased} estimator of the population variance:
\code{E[s^2(n)] = sigma^2} for every \code{n >= 2}. The expected
curve is therefore essentially \strong{flat}; what changes with \code{n} is not
its level but its \emph{precision} -- the resampling band narrows as \code{n}
grows. "Stabilisation" here is therefore convergence of the estimate
in \emph{precision}, not in level: \verb{n*} is defined as the smallest \code{n}
beyond which the resampling band's half-width, relative to the
full-sample value \code{V(N_g)}, stays at or below \code{conv_tol} for all
larger sub-sample sizes (framing \code{"convergence"}). Basing this on the
band rather than the mean is deliberate: because \code{E[s^2(n)]} is
flat, a criterion on the mean would return \verb{n* = 2} trivially,
whereas the band width is what actually decreases with sampling
effort. This answers: \emph{how many individuals are needed for a reliable
(well-pinned-down) estimate of intraspecific variability?}}
\item{\strong{Accumulation metrics} (\code{"range"})}{The observed range (and,
more generally, the amount of trait space occupied) genuinely
\emph{increases} with \code{n} and saturates, exactly like species richness in
a rarefaction curve. Here a saturating model is fitted to the curve
(Michaelis-Menten \code{V(n) = Vmax * n / (K + n)} or negative
exponential \code{V(n) = Vmax * (1 - exp(-b*n))}) and \verb{n*} is the
sample size reaching a fraction \code{asymptote_prop} of the estimated
asymptote \code{Vmax} (framing \code{"accumulation"}). For
Michaelis-Menten this is available in closed form,
\verb{n* = K * p / (1 - p)}; for the exponential model,
\verb{n* = -log(1 - p) / b}. When the metric has not saturated within
the observed range (e.g. the range of an unbounded, approximately
Gaussian trait, which grows without a true asymptote), \verb{n*} may
exceed \code{n_max} -- this is a legitimate \emph{extrapolation} signalling
that more individuals than were sampled would be needed to reach
\code{asymptote_prop} of the fitted asymptote, and should be read
alongside \code{prop_reached} (the fraction of the asymptote actually
attained at N_g).}
}

\code{"variance"} is multivariate: it uses the trace of the group trait
covariance matrix (the sum of the per-trait variances), the same
dispersion measure returned by \code{\link[=trait_disparity]{trait_disparity()}}, so a single curve is
produced per group. \code{"sd"}, \code{"cv"} and \code{"range"} are univariate and
produce one curve per group \emph{and} trait.

The \code{n_perm} random draws at each sub-sample size are independent of one
another and are distributed automatically across \code{future.apply}'s workers
when that (Suggested) package is installed and a parallel
\code{\link[future:plan]{future::plan()}} has been set beforehand; otherwise this runs
sequentially, with identical results (see \code{\link[=bootstrap_functional_space]{bootstrap_functional_space()}},
\code{\link[=trait_disparity]{trait_disparity()}}). Exact reproducibility across runs therefore
requires either a sequential plan together with \code{seed}, or reliance on
\code{future.apply}'s own parallel-safe streams.
}
